---
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import Callout from "../components/Callout.astro";
import ContentLayout from "../layouts/ContentLayout.astro";
import { sitePath } from "../utils/sitePath";

const loosePrompt = "Review this bugfix carefully. Stay read-only. Watch for behavior changes and missing tests. Do not edit code unless I approve a fix.";

const contractPrompt = "Operate under behavior-review. Review the current diff and report findings.";

const handoffCommands = `personakit validate --root .personakit
personakit contract --root .personakit --session behavior-review
personakit export --root .personakit --session behavior-review`;
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Learn PersonaKit"
  eyebrow="Mental map"
  description="Place PersonaKit among prompts, skills, harnesses, MCP, CLI tools, and coding agents."
>
  <p>PersonaKit makes the most sense when you stop asking whether it replaces prompts or skills. It does not. PersonaKit is the operating-contract layer that says which role, rules, context, stop points, and capabilities apply before a model-backed worker starts.</p>

  <div class="learning-map">
    <a href="#map">Map the layers</a>
    <a href="#contract">Read the contract</a>
    <a href="#compose">Compose the pieces</a>
    <a href="#prompt-to-contract">Turn a prompt into a contract</a>
    <a href="#handoff">Export handoff context</a>
  </div>

  <h2 id="map">Map The Layers</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Layer</th>
        <th>Plain Job</th>
        <th>PersonaKit Relationship</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Prompt</td>
        <td>A one-time expression of intent.</td>
        <td>PersonaKit keeps durable rules out of the prompt so the task text can stay small.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Saved prompt</td>
        <td>Reusable text that still has to be copied or remembered.</td>
        <td>PersonaKit turns repeated setup into structured, inspectable project context.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Skill</td>
        <td>A local procedure, helper, or capability.</td>
        <td>PersonaKit can declare whether that capability is allowed or forbidden for a work mode.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Harness</td>
        <td>The wrapper that calls models, tools, or agent runtimes.</td>
        <td>PersonaKit produces the contract a harness can pass into the worker.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>MCP</td>
        <td>A protocol surface for context, tools, prompts, and provenance.</td>
        <td>PersonaKit MCP exposes read-only grounding so clients can resolve contracts before action.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>CLI</td>
        <td>The practical local interface for validation, inspection, and export.</td>
        <td>PersonaKit CLI proves the contract before another coding tool starts work.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Agent</td>
        <td>The worker that reads context and performs the task.</td>
        <td>PersonaKit prepares the agent. It does not become the agent.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <Callout>
    <p><strong>Working definition:</strong> PersonaKit resolves an operating contract for repeated AI coding work.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="contract">Read The Contract</h2>
  <p>A resolved contract answers the questions that usually get scattered through chat history.</p>

  <div class="grid two">
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Who Is Working?</h3>
      <p>The persona defines responsibilities, values, and non-goals.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>What Kind Of Work?</h3>
      <p>The directive defines steps, acceptance criteria, verification, and stop points.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Which Rules Apply?</h3>
      <p>Kits and essentials carry durable project guidance into the resolved payload.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Which Capabilities Are Allowed?</h3>
      <p>Skill authorization makes allowed and forbidden capabilities visible before work begins.</p>
    </article>
  </div>

  <h2 id="compose">Compose The Pieces</h2>
  <p>PersonaKit contracts are assembled from reusable parts. Operators should not have to copy the same careful-review paragraph into every prompt or maintain several nearly identical skills just to change a boundary.</p>

  <div class="grid three compose-grid">
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Persona</h3>
      <p>Who is acting.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Directive</h3>
      <p>What kind of work this is.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Kit</h3>
      <p>Rules that should travel across related sessions.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Essentials</h3>
      <p>Required grounding that belongs in the resolved payload.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Skills</h3>
      <p>Capabilities that may be authorized or forbidden for this lane.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Session</h3>
      <p>The composed lane that selects the pieces to resolve together.</p>
    </article>
  </div>

  <h3 class="composition-heading">Review Composition Example</h3>
  <p class="composition-intro">Review work shows why the pieces stay separate:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Composition</th>
        <th>Result</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>behavior-reviewer</code> + <code>behavior-preserving-review</code></td>
        <td>The existing read-only review lane reports findings without becoming the implementer.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Same reviewer + a different directive and session</td>
        <td>A conceptual implementation-after-approval lane could be separate instead of mutating the read-only lane.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Shared review kit or essential</td>
        <td>Review discipline can travel across lanes without being pasted into each task prompt.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Same skill catalog, different sessions</td>
        <td>A capability can stay reusable while authorization is decided by the resolved contract.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="prompt-to-contract">Turn A Prompt Into A Contract</h2>
  <p>Start with a loose prompt:</p>

  <Code code={loosePrompt} lang="text" theme="github-dark" />

  <p>PersonaKit asks which parts are durable enough to become reusable structure:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Prompt Fragment</th>
        <th>Contract Piece</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Review this bugfix carefully.</td>
        <td>Persona: behavior reviewer.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Stay read-only.</td>
        <td>Skill boundary: authorize review, forbid editing.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Watch for behavior changes and missing tests.</td>
        <td>Directive: review steps and acceptance criteria.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Do not edit code unless I approve a fix.</td>
        <td>Stop point: implementation requires human approval.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>The next prompt can shrink because the contract carries the repeated setup:</p>

  <Code code={contractPrompt} lang="text" theme="github-dark" />

  <p><a class="button-link" href={sitePath("examples/review-session/")}>Study the review-session example</a></p>

  <h2 id="handoff">Export Handoff Context</h2>
  <p>The practical loop is small and inspectable:</p>

  <ol>
    <li>Validate the authored PersonaKit root.</li>
    <li>Resolve the session contract.</li>
    <li>Inspect or export the context.</li>
    <li>Copy the exported grounding into the coding tool you use for the actual work.</li>
  </ol>

  <Code code={handoffCommands} lang="bash" theme="github-dark" />

  <Callout tone="good">
    <p>That is the craft: make the boundary durable, inspect it, and hand off only the context the contract resolved.</p>
  </Callout>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .learning-map {
    display: grid;
    gap: 10px;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(5, minmax(0, 1fr));
    margin: 24px 0 36px;
  }

  .learning-map a {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    min-height: 54px;
    padding: 10px 12px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 8px;
    color: var(--ink);
    background: #fff;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .learning-map a:hover {
    border-color: #9fb7c6;
    color: var(--blue);
  }

  .compose-grid {
    margin: 18px 0 30px;
  }

  .composition-heading {
    margin: 0 0 8px;
  }

  .composition-intro {
    margin-bottom: 14px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 840px) {
    .learning-map {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    }
  }

  @media (max-width: 520px) {
    .learning-map {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
